# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mass-spectrometry-proteomics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Mass spectrometry using ESI is called electrospray ionization mass spectrometry (ESI-MS) or, less commonly, electrospray mass spectrometry (ES-MS).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] ESI is a so-called 'soft ionization' technique, since there is very little fragmentation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] This can be advantageous in the sense that the molecular ion (or more accurately a pseudo molecular ion) is almost always observed, however very little structural information can be gained from the simple mass spectrum obtained.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] This disadvantage can be overcome by coupling ESI with tandem mass spectrometry (ESI-MS/MS).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Another important advantage of ESI is that solution-phase information can be retained into the gas-phase.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] The electrospray ionization technique was first reported by Masamichi Yamashita and John Fenn in 1984, and independently by Lidia Gall and co-workers in Soviet Union, also in 1984.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Gall's work was not recognised or translated in the western scientific literature until a translation was published in 2008.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] The development of electrospray ionization for the analysis of biological macromolecules was rewarded with the attribution of the Nobel Prize in Chemistry to John Bennett Fenn and Koichi Tanaka in 2002.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] One of the original instruments used by Fenn is on display at the Science History Institute in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] In 1882, Lord Rayleigh theoretically estimated the maximum amount of charge a liquid droplet could carry before throwing out fine jets of liquid.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] This is now known as the Rayleigh limit.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] In 1914, John Zeleny published work on the behaviour of fluid droplets at the end of glass capillaries and presented evidence for different electrospray modes.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Wilson and Taylor and Nolan investigated electrospray in the 1920s and Macky in 1931.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] The electrospray cone (now known as the Taylor cone) was described by Sir Geoffrey Ingram Taylor.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] The first use of electrospray ionization with mass spectrometry was reported by Malcolm Dole in 1968.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] John Bennett Fenn was awarded the 2002 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for the development of electrospray ionization mass spectrometry in the late 1980s.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] The liquid containing the analytes of interest (typically 10−6 - 10−4 M needed ) is dispersed by electrospray, into a fine aerosol.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Because the ion formation involves extensive solvent evaporation (also termed desolvation), the typical solvents for electrospray ionization are prepared by mixing water with volatile organic compounds (e.g. methanol acetonitrile).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] To decrease the initial droplet size, compounds that increase the conductivity (e.g. acetic acid) are customarily added to the solution.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] These species also act to provide a source of protons to facilitate the ionization process.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Large-flow electrosprays can benefit from nebulization of a heated inert gas such as nitrogen or carbon dioxide in addition to the high temperature of the ESI source.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] The aerosol is sampled into the first vacuum stage of a mass spectrometer through a capillary carrying a potential difference of approximately 3000 V, which can be heated to aid further solvent evaporation from the charged droplets.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] The solvent evaporates from a charged droplet until it becomes unstable upon reaching its Rayleigh limit.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] At this point, the droplet deforms as the electrostatic repulsion of like charges, in an ever-decreasing droplet size, becomes more powerful than the surface tension holding the droplet together.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] At this point the droplet undergoes Coulomb fission, whereby the original droplet 'explodes' creating many smaller, more stable droplets.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] The new droplets undergo desolvation and subsequently further Coulomb fissions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] During the fission, the droplet loses a small percentage of its mass (1.0–2.3%) along with a relatively large percentage of its charge (10–18%).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] There are two major theories that explain the final production of gas-phase ions: the ion evaporation model (IEM) and the charge residue model (CRM).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] The IEM suggests that as the droplet reaches a certain radius the field strength at the surface of the droplet becomes large enough to assist the field desorption of solvated ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] The CRM suggests that electrospray droplets undergo evaporation and fission cycles, eventually leading progeny droplets that contain on average one analyte ion or less.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] The gas-phase ions form after the remaining solvent molecules evaporate, leaving the analyte with the charges that the droplet carried.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] A large body of evidence shows either directly or indirectly that small ions (from small molecules) are liberated into the gas phase through the ion evaporation mechanism, while larger ions (from folded proteins for instance) form by charged residue mechanism.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] A third model invoking combined charged residue-field emission has been proposed.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Another model called chain ejection model (CEM) is proposed for disordered polymers (unfolded proteins).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] The ions observed by mass spectrometry may be quasimolecular ions created by the addition of a hydrogen cation and denoted [**M** + H]+, or of another cation such as sodium ion, [**M** + Na]+, or the removal of a hydrogen nucleus, [**M** − H]−.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Multiply charged ions such as [**M** + *n*H]*n*+ are often observed.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] For large macromolecules, there can be many charge states, resulting in a characteristic charge state envelope.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] All these are even-electron ion species: electrons (alone) are not added or removed, unlike in some other ionization sources.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] The analytes are sometimes involved in electrochemical processes, leading to shifts of the corresponding peaks in the mass spectrum.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] This effect is demonstrated in the direct ionization of noble metals such as copper, silver and gold using electrospray.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] The efficiency of generating the gas phase ions for small molecules in ESI varies depending on the compound structure, the solvent used and instrumental parameters.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] The differences in ionization efficiency reach more than 1 million times.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] The electrosprays operated at low flow rates generate much smaller initial droplets, which ensure improved ionization efficiency.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Smith reported significant sensitivity increases could be achieved using lower flow rates, and down to 200 nL/min.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] In 1994, two research groups coined the name micro-electrospray (microspray) for electrosprays working at low flow rates.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Emmett and Caprioli demonstrated improved performance for HPLC-MS analyses when the electrospray was operated at 300–800 nL/min.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Wilm and Mann demonstrated that a capillary flow of ~ 25 nL/min can sustain an electrospray at the tip of emitters fabricated by pulling glass capillaries to a few micrometers.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] The latter was renamed nano-electrospray (nanospray) in 1996.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Currently the name nanospray is also in use for electrosprays fed by pumps at low flow rates, not only for self-fed electrosprays.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Although there may not be a well-defined flow rate range for electrospray, microspray, and nano-electrospray, studied "changes in analyte partition during droplet fission prior to ion release".
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] In this paper, they compare results obtained by three other groups. and then measure the signal intensity ratio [Ba2+ + Ba+]/[BaBr+] at different flow rates.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Cold spray ionization is a form of electrospray in which the solution containing the sample is forced through a small cold capillary (10–80 °C) into an electric field to create a fine mist of cold charged droplets.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Applications of this method include the analysis of fragile molecules and guest-host interactions that cannot be studied using regular electrospray ionization.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Electrospray ionization has also been achieved at pressures as low as 25 torr and termed subambient pressure ionization with nanoelectrospray (SPIN) based upon a two-stage ion funnel interface developed by Richard D.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] The SPIN implementation provided increased sensitivity due to the use of ion funnels that helped confine and transfer ions to the lower pressure region of the mass spectrometer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Nanoelectrospray emitter is made out of a fine capillary with a small aperture about 1–3 micrometer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] For sufficient conductivity this capillary is usually sputter-coated with conductive material, e.g. gold.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Nanoelectrospray ionization consumes only a few microliters of a sample and forms smaller droplets.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Operation at low pressure was particularly effective for low flow rates where the smaller electrospray droplet size allowed effective desolvation and ion formation to be achieved.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] As a result, the researchers were later able to demonstrate achieving an excess of 50% overall ionization utilization efficiency for transfer of ions from the liquid phase, into the gas phase as ions, and through the dual ion funnel interface to the mass spectrometer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] In ambient ionization, the formation of ions occurs outside the mass spectrometer without sample preparation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Electrospray is used for ion formation in a number of ambient ion sources.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Desorption electrospray ionization (DESI) is an ambient ionization technique in which a solvent electrospray is directed at a sample.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] The electrospray is attracted to the surface by applying a voltage to the sample.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Sample compounds are extracted into the solvent which is again aerosolized as highly charged droplets that evaporate to form highly charged ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] After ionization, the ions enter the atmospheric pressure interface of the mass spectrometer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] DESI allows for ambient ionization of samples at atmospheric pressure, with little sample preparation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Extractive electrospray ionization is a spray-type, ambient ionization method that uses two merged sprays, one of which is generated by electrospray.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Laser-based electrospray-based ambient ionization is a two-step process in which a pulsed laser is used to desorb or ablate material from a sample and the plume of material interacts with an electrospray to create ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] For ambient ionization, the sample material is deposited on a target near the electrospray.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] The laser desorbs or ablates material from the sample which is ejected from the surface and into the electrospray which produces highly charged ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Examples are electrospray laser desorption ionization, matrix-assisted laser desorption electrospray ionization, and laser ablation electrospray ionization.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Electrostatic spray ionization (ESTASI) involved the analysis of samples located on a flat or porous surface, or inside a microchannel.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] A droplet containing analytes is deposited on a sample area, to which a pulsed high voltage to is applied.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] When the electrostatic pressure is larger than the surface tension, droplets and ions are sprayed.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Secondary electrospray ionization (SESI) is an spray type, ambient ionization method where charging ions are produced by means of an electrospray.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] These ions then charge vapor molecules in the gas phase when colliding with them.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] In paper spray ionization, the sample is applied to a piece of paper, solvent is added, and a high voltage is applied to the paper, creating ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Electrospray is used to study protein folding.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Electrospray ionization is the ion source of choice to couple liquid chromatography with mass spectrometry (LC-MS).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] The analysis can be performed online, by feeding the liquid eluting from the LC column directly to an electrospray, or offline, by collecting fractions to be later analyzed in a classical nanoelectrospray-mass spectrometry setup.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Among the numerous operating parameters in ESI-MS, for proteins, the electrospray voltage has been identified as an important parameter to consider in ESI LC/MS gradient elution.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] The effect of various solvent compositions (such as TFA or ammonium acetate, or supercharging reagents, or derivitizing groups) or spraying conditions on electrospray-LCMS spectra and/or nanoESI-MS spectra. have been studied.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Capillary electrophoresis-mass spectrometry was enabled by an ESI interface that was developed and patented by Richard D.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Smith and coworkers at Pacific Northwest National Laboratory, and shown to have broad utility for the analysis of very small biological and chemical compound mixtures, and even extending to a single biological cell.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Electrospray ionization is also utilized in studying noncovalent gas phase interactions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] The electrospray process is thought to be capable of transferring liquid-phase noncovalent complexes into the gas phase without disrupting the noncovalent interaction.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Problems such as non specific interactions have been identified when studying ligand substrate complexes by ESI-MS or nanoESI-MS.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] An interesting example of this is studying the interactions between enzymes and drugs which are inhibitors of the enzyme.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Competition studies between STAT6 and inhibitors have used ESI as a way to screen for potential new drug candidates.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/electrospray-ionization] Electrospray ionization can even be used for studying protein complexes >1 MDa.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/isobaric-labeling] The most common isobaric tags are amine-reactive tags.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/isobaric-labeling] However, tags that react with cysteine residues and carbonyl groups have also been described.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/isobaric-labeling] These amine-reactive groups go through N-hydroxysuccinimide (NHS) reactions, which are based around three types of functional groups.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/isobaric-labeling] Isobaric labeling methods include tandem mass tags (TMT), isobaric tags for relative and absolute quantification (iTRAQ), mass differential tags for absolute and relative quantification, and dimethyl labeling.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/isobaric-labeling] TMTs and iTRAQ methods are most common and developed of these methods.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/isobaric-labeling] Tandem mass tags have a mass reporter region, a cleavable linker region, a mass normalization region, and a protein reactive group and have the same total mass.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/isobaric-labeling] A typical bottom-up proteomics workflow is described by (Yates, 2014).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/isobaric-labeling] Protein samples are enzymatically digested by a protease to produce peptides.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/isobaric-labeling] Each digested experimental sample is derivative from a set with a different isotopic variant of the tag.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/isobaric-labeling] The samples are mixed in typically equal ratios and analyzed simultaneously in one MS run.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/isobaric-labeling] Since the tags are isobaric and have identical chemical properties, the isotopic variants of the tags appear as a single composite peak at the same m/z value in an MS1 scan with identical liquid chromatography (LC) retention times.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/isobaric-labeling] During the MS2 analysis and upon fragmentation, each isotopic variant of the tag produces sequence-specific product ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/isobaric-labeling] These product ions are used to determine the peptide sequence and the reporter tags whose abundances reflect the relative ratio of the peptide in the combined samples.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/isobaric-labeling] The use of MS/MS is required to detect the tags, therefore, unlabeled peptides are not quantified.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/isobaric-labeling] Explained previously by (Lee, Choe, Aggarwal, 2017).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/isobaric-labeling] A key benefit of isobaric labeling over other quantification techniques (e.g. label-free) is the multiplex capabilities and thus increased throughput potential.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/isobaric-labeling] The ability to combine and analyze several samples simultaneously in one LC-MS run eliminates the need to analyze multiple data sets and eliminates run-to-run variation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/isobaric-labeling] Multiplexing reduces sample processing variability, improves specificity by quantifying the peptides from each condition simultaneously, and reduces turnaround time for multiple samples.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/isobaric-labeling] Without multiplexing, information can be missed from run to run, affecting identification and quantification, as peptides selected for fragmentation on one LC-MS/MS run may not be present or of suitable quantity in subsequent sample runs.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/isobaric-labeling] The current available isobaric chemical tags facilitate the simultaneous analysis of 2 to 11 experimental samples.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/isobaric-labeling] There are two types of isobaric tags commercially available: tandem mass tags (TMT) and isobaric tags for relative and absolute quantitation (iTRAQ).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/isobaric-labeling] Amine-reactive TMT are available in duplex, 6-plex 10-plex, and now 11-plex sets.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/isobaric-labeling] Amine-reactive iTRAQ are available in 4-plex and 8-plex forms.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] In mass spectrometry, **matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization** (**MALDI**) is an ionization technique that uses a laser energy-absorbing matrix to create ions from large molecules with minimal fragmentation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] It has been applied to the analysis of biomolecules (biopolymers such as DNA, proteins, peptides and carbohydrates) and various organic molecules (such as polymers, dendrimers and other macromolecules), which tend to be fragile and fragment when ionized by more conventional ionization methods.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] It is similar in character to electrospray ionization (ESI) in that both techniques are relatively soft (low fragmentation) ways of obtaining ions of large molecules in the gas phase, though MALDI typically produces far fewer multi-charged ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] MALDI methodology is a three-step process.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] First, the sample is mixed with a suitable matrix material and applied to a metal plate.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Second, a pulsed laser irradiates the sample, triggering ablation and desorption of the sample and matrix material.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Finally, the analyte molecules are ionized by being protonated or deprotonated in the hot plume of ablated gases, and then they can be accelerated into whichever mass spectrometer is used to analyse them.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The term matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization (MALDI) was coined in 1985 by Franz Hillenkamp, Michael Karas and their colleagues.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] These researchers found that the amino acid alanine could be ionized more easily if it was mixed with the amino acid tryptophan and irradiated with a pulsed 266 nm laser.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The tryptophan was absorbing the laser energy and helping to ionize the non-absorbing alanine.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Peptides up to the 2843 Da peptide melittin could be ionized when mixed with this kind of "matrix".
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Using this laser and matrix combination, Tanaka was able to ionize biomolecules as large as the 34,472 Da protein carboxypeptidase-A.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Tanaka received one-quarter of the 2002 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for demonstrating that, with the proper combination of laser wavelength and matrix, a protein can be ionized.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Karas and Hillenkamp were subsequently able to ionize the 67 kDa protein albumin using a nicotinic acid matrix and a 266 nm laser.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Further improvements were realized through the use of a 355 nm laser and the cinnamic acid derivatives ferulic acid, caffeic acid and sinapinic acid as the matrix.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The availability of small and relatively inexpensive nitrogen lasers operating at 337 nm wavelength and the first commercial instruments introduced in the early 1990s brought MALDI to an increasing number of researchers.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Today, mostly organic matrices are used for MALDI mass spectrometry.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The matrix consists of crystallized molecules, of which the three most commonly used are sinapinic acid, α-cyano-4-hydroxycinnamic acid (α-CHCA, alpha-cyano or alpha-matrix) and 2,5-dihydroxybenzoic acid (DHB).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] A solution of one of these molecules is made, often in a mixture of highly purified water and an organic solvent such as acetonitrile (ACN) or ethanol.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] A counter ion source such as trifluoroacetic acid (TFA) is usually added to generate the [M+H] ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] A good example of a matrix-solution would be 20 mg/mL sinapinic acid in ACN:water:TFA (50:50:0.1).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The identification of suitable matrix compounds is determined to some extent by trial and error, but they are based on some specific molecular design considerations.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] They are of a fairly low molecular weight (to allow easy vaporization), but are large enough (with a low enough vapor pressure) not to evaporate during sample preparation or while standing in the mass spectrometer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] They are often acidic, therefore act as a proton source to encourage ionization of the analyte.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] They have a strong optical absorption in either the UV or IR range, so that they rapidly and efficiently absorb the laser irradiation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] This efficiency is commonly associated with chemical structures incorporating several conjugated double bonds, as seen in the structure of cinnamic acid.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] They are functionalized with polar groups, allowing their use in aqueous solutions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The matrix solution is mixed with the analyte (e.g. protein-sample).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] A mixture of water and organic solvent allows both hydrophobic and water-soluble (hydrophilic) molecules to dissolve into the solution.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] This solution is spotted onto a MALDI plate (usually a metal plate designed for this purpose).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The solvents vaporize, leaving only the recrystallized matrix, but now with analyte molecules embedded into MALDI crystals.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The matrix and the analyte are said to be co-crystallized.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Co-crystallization is a key issue in selecting a proper matrix to obtain a good quality mass spectrum of the analyte of interest.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] In analysis of biological systems, inorganic salts, which are also part of protein extracts, interfere with the ionization process.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The salts can be removed by solid phase extraction or by washing the dried-droplet MALDI spots with cold water.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Both methods can also remove other substances from the sample.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The matrix-protein mixture is not homogeneous because the polarity difference leads to a separation of the two substances during co-crystallization.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The spot diameter of the target is much larger than that of the laser, which makes it necessary to make many laser shots at different places of the target, to get the statistical average of the substance concentration within the target spot.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The matrix can be used to tune the instrument to ionize the sample in different ways.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] As mentioned above, acid-base like reactions are often utilized to ionize the sample, however, molecules with conjugated pi systems, such as naphthalene like compounds, can also serve as an electron acceptor and thus a matrix for MALDI/TOF.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] This is particularly useful in studying molecules that also possess conjugated pi systems.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The most widely used application for these matrices is studying porphyrin-like compounds such as chlorophyll.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] These matrices have been shown to have better ionization patterns that do not result in odd fragmentation patterns or complete loss of side chains.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] It has also been suggested that conjugated porphyrin like molecules can serve as a matrix and cleave themselves eliminating the need for a separate matrix compound.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] There are several variations of the MALDI technology and comparable instruments are today produced for very different purposes, from more academic and analytical, to more industrial and high throughput.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The mass spectrometry field has expanded into requiring ultrahigh resolution mass spectrometry such as the FT-ICR instruments as well as more high-throughput instruments.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] As many MALDI MS instruments can be bought with an interchangeable ionization source (electrospray ionization, MALDI, atmospheric pressure ionization, etc.) the technologies often overlap and many times any soft ionization method could potentially be used.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] For more variations of soft ionization methods see: Soft laser desorption or Ion source.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] MALDI techniques typically employ the use of UV lasers such as nitrogen lasers (337 nm) and frequency-tripled and quadrupled Nd:YAG lasers (355 nm and 266 nm respectively).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Infrared laser wavelengths used for infrared MALDI include the 2.94 μm Er:YAG laser, mid-IR optical parametric oscillator, and 10.6 μm carbon dioxide laser.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Although not as common, infrared lasers are used due to their softer mode of ionization.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] IR-MALDI also has the advantage of greater material removal (useful for biological samples), less low-mass interference, and compatibility with other matrix-free laser desorption mass spectrometry methods.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The type of a mass spectrometer most widely used with MALDI is the time-of-flight mass spectrometer (TOF), mainly due to its large mass range.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The TOF measurement procedure is also ideally suited to the MALDI ionization process since the pulsed laser takes individual 'shots' rather than working in continuous operation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] MALDI-TOF instruments are often equipped with a reflectron (an "ion mirror") that reflects ions using an electric field.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] This increases the ion flight path, thereby increasing time of flight between ions of different m/z and increasing resolution.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Modern commercial reflectron TOF instruments reach a resolving power m/Δm of 50,000 FWHM (full-width half-maximum, Δm defined as the peak width at 50% of peak height) or more.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] MALDI has been coupled with IMS-TOF MS to identify phosphorylated and non-phosphorylated peptides.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] MALDI-FT-ICR MS has been demonstrated to be a useful technique where high resolution MALDI-MS measurements are desired.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Atmospheric pressure (AP) matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization (MALDI) is an ionization technique (ion source) that in contrast to vacuum MALDI operates at normal atmospheric environment.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The main difference between vacuum MALDI and AP-MALDI is the pressure in which the ions are created.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] In vacuum MALDI, ions are typically produced at 10 mTorr or less while in AP-MALDI ions are formed in atmospheric pressure.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] In the past, the main disadvantage of the AP-MALDI technique compared to the conventional vacuum MALDI has been its limited sensitivity; however, ions can be transferred into the mass spectrometer with high efficiency and attomole detection limits have been reported.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] AP-MALDI is used in mass spectrometry (MS) in a variety of applications ranging from proteomics to drug discovery.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Popular topics that are addressed by AP-MALDI mass spectrometry include: proteomics; mass analysis of DNA, RNA, PNA, lipids, oligosaccharides, phosphopeptides, bacteria, small molecules and synthetic polymers, similar applications as available also for vacuum MALDI instruments.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The AP-MALDI ion source is easily coupled to an ion trap mass spectrometer or any other MS system equipped with electrospray ionization (ESI) or nanoESI source.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] MALDI with ionization at reduced pressure is known to produce mainly singly-charged ions (see "Ionization mechanism" below).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] In contrast, ionization at atmospheric pressure can generate highly-charged analytes as was first shown for infrared and later also for nitrogen lasers.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Multiple charging of analytes is of great importance, because it allows to measure high-molecular-weight compounds like proteins in instruments, which provide only smaller *m/z* detection ranges such as quadrupoles.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Besides the pressure, the composition of the matrix is important to achieve this effect.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] In aerosol mass spectrometry, one of the ionization techniques consists in firing a laser to individual droplets.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] These systems are called single particle mass spectrometers (SPMS).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The sample may optionally be mixed with a MALDI matrix prior to aerosolization.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The laser is fired at the matrix crystals in the dried-droplet spot.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The matrix absorbs the laser energy and it is thought that primarily the matrix is desorbed and ionized (by addition of a proton) by this event.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The hot plume produced during ablation contains many species: neutral and ionized matrix molecules, protonated and deprotonated matrix molecules, matrix clusters and nanodroplets.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Ablated species may participate in the ionization of analyte, though the mechanism of MALDI is still debated.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The matrix is then thought to transfer protons to the analyte molecules (e.g., protein molecules), thus charging the analyte.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] An ion observed after this process will consist of the initial neutral molecule [M] with ions added or removed.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] This is called a quasimolecular ion, for example [M+H]+ in the case of an added proton, [M+Na]+ in the case of an added sodium ion, or [M-H]− in the case of a removed proton.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] MALDI is capable of creating singly charged ions or multiply charged ions ([M+nH]n+) depending on the nature of the matrix, the laser intensity, and/or the voltage used.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Note that these are all even-electron species.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Ion signals of radical cations (photoionized molecules) can be observed, e.g., in the case of matrix molecules and other organic molecules.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The gas phase proton transfer model, implemented as the coupled physical and chemical dynamics (CPCD) model, of UV laser MALDI postulates primary and secondary processes leading to ionization.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Primary processes involve initial charge separation through absorption of photons by the matrix and pooling of the energy to form matrix ion pairs.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] where S0 is the ground electronic state, S1 the first electronic excited state, and Sn is a higher electronic excited state.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The product ions can be proton transfer or electron transfer ion pairs, indicated by M+ and M− above.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Secondary processes involve ion-molecule reactions to form analyte ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The lucky survivor model (cluster ionization mechanism) postulates that analyte molecules are incorporated in the matrix maintaining the charge state from solution.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Ion formation occurs through charge separation upon fragmentation of laser ablated clusters.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Ions that are not neutralized by recombination with photoelectrons or counter ions are the so-called lucky survivors.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The thermal model postulates that the high temperature facilitates the proton transfer between matrix and analyte in melted matrix liquid.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Ion-to-neutral ratio is an important parameter to justify the theoretical model, and the mistaken citation of ion-to-neutral ratio could result in an erroneous determination of the ionization mechanism.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The model quantitatively predicts the increase in total ion intensity as a function of the concentration and proton affinity of the analytes, and the ion-to-neutral ratio as a function of the laser fluences.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] This model also suggests that metal ion adducts (e.g., [M+Na]+ or [M+K]+) are mainly generated from the thermally induced dissolution of salt.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The matrix-assisted ionization (MAI) method uses matrix preparation similar to MALDI but does not require laser ablation to produce analyte ions of volatile or nonvolatile compounds.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Simply exposing the matrix with analyte to the vacuum of the mass spectrometer creates ions with nearly identical charge states to electrospray ionization.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] It is suggested that there are likely mechanistic commonality between this process and MALDI.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Ion yield is typically estimated to range from 10−4 to 10−7, with some experiments hinting to even lower yields of 10−9.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The issue of low ion yields had been addressed, already shortly after introduction of MALDI by various attempts, including post-ionization utilizing a second laser.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Most of these attempts showed only limited success, with low signal increases.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] This might be attributed to the fact that axial time-of-flight instruments were used, which operate at pressures in the source region of 10−5 to 10−6, which results in rapid plume expansion with particle velocities of up to 1000 m/s.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] This approach, called MALDI-2, due to the second laser, and the second MALDI-like ionization process, was afterwards adopted for other mass spectrometers, all equipped with sources operating in the low mbar range.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] In proteomics, MALDI is used for the rapid identification of proteins isolated by using gel electrophoresis: SDS-PAGE, size exclusion chromatography, affinity chromatography, strong/weak ion exchange, isotope coded protein labeling (ICPL), and two-dimensional gel electrophoresis.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Peptide mass fingerprinting is the most popular analytical application of MALDI-TOF mass spectrometers.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] MALDI TOF/TOF mass spectrometers are used to reveal amino acid sequence of peptides using post-source decay or high energy collision-induced dissociation (further use see mass spectrometry).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] MALDI-TOF have been used to characterise post-translational modifications.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] For example, it has been widely applied to study protein methylation and demethylation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] However, care must be taken when studying post-translational modifications by MALDI-TOF.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] For example, it has been reported that loss of sialic acid has been identified in papers when dihydroxybenzoic acid (DHB) has been used as a matrix for MALDI MS analysis of glycosylated peptides.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Using sinapinic acid, 4-HCCA and DHB as matrices, S.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Martin studied loss of sialic acid in glycosylated peptides by metastable decay in MALDI/TOF in linear mode and reflector mode.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] A group at Shimadzu Corporation derivatized the sialic acid by an amidation reaction as a way to improve detection sensitivity and also demonstrated that ionic liquid matrix reduces a loss of sialic acid during MALDI/TOF MS analysis of sialylated oligosaccharides.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] THAP, DHAP, and a mixture of 2-aza-2-thiothymine and phenylhydrazine have been identified as matrices that could be used to minimize loss of sialic acid during MALDI MS analysis of glycosylated peptides.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] It has been reported that a reduction in loss of some post-translational modifications can be accomplished if IR MALDI is used instead of UV MALDI.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Besides proteins, MALDI-TOF has also been applied to study lipids.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] For example, it has been applied to study the catalytic reactions of phospholipases.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] In addition to lipids, oligonucleotides have also been characterised by MALDI-TOF.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] For example, in molecular biology, a mixture of 5-methoxysalicylic acid and spermine can be used as a matrix for oligonucleotides analysis in MALDI mass spectrometry, for instance after oligonucleotide synthesis.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Some synthetic macromolecules, such as catenanes and rotaxanes, dendrimers and hyperbranched polymers, and other assemblies, have molecular weights extending into the thousands or tens of thousands, where most ionization techniques have difficulty producing molecular ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] MALDI is a simple and fast analytical method that can allow chemists to rapidly analyze the results of such syntheses and verify their results.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] In polymer chemistry, MALDI can be used to determine the molar mass distribution.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Polymers with polydispersity greater than 1.2 are difficult to characterize with MALDI due to the signal intensity discrimination against higher mass oligomers.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] A good matrix for polymers is dithranol or AgTFA.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The sample must first be mixed with dithranol and the AgTFA added afterwards; otherwise the sample will precipitate out of solution.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] MALDI-TOF spectra are often used for the identification of microorganisms such as bacteria or fungi.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] A portion of a colony of the microbe in question is placed onto the sample target and overlaid with matrix.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The mass spectra of expressed proteins generated are analyzed by dedicated software and compared with stored profiles for species determination in what is known as biotyping.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] It offers benefits to other immunological or biochemical procedures and has become a common method for species identification in clinical microbiological laboratories.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Benefits of high resolution MALDI-MS performed on a Fourier transform ion cyclotron resonance mass spectrometry (also known as FT-MS) have been demonstrated for typing and subtyping viruses though single ion detection known as proteotyping, with a particular focus on influenza viruses.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] One main advantage over other microbiological identification methods is its ability to rapidly and reliably identify, at low cost, a wide variety of microorganisms directly from the selective medium used to isolate them.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The absence of the need to purify the suspect or "presumptive" colony allows for a much faster turn-around times.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] For example, it has been demonstrated that MALDI-TOF can be used to detect bacteria directly from blood cultures.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Another advantage is the potential to predict antibiotic susceptibility of bacteria.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] A single mass spectral peak can predict methicillin resistance of *Staphylococcus aureus*.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] MALDI can also detect carbapenemase of carbapenem-resistant enterobacteriaceae, including *Acinetobacter baumannii* and *Klebsiella pneumoniae*.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] MALDI-TOF spectra have been used for the detection and identification of various parasites such as trypanosomatids, *Leishmania* and *Plasmodium*.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] In addition to these unicellular parasites, MALDI/TOF can be used for the identification of parasitic insects such as lice or cercariae, the free-swimming stage of trematodes.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] MALDI-TOF spectra are often utilized in tandem with other analysis and spectroscopy techniques in the diagnosis of diseases.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] MALDI/TOF is a diagnostic tool with much potential because it allows for the rapid identification of proteins and changes to proteins without the cost or computing power of sequencing nor the skill or time needed to solve a crystal structure in X-ray crystallography.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] One example of this is necrotizing enterocolitis (NEC), which is a devastating disease that affects the bowels of premature infants.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The symptoms of NEC are very similar to those of sepsis, and many infants die awaiting diagnosis and treatment.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] MALDI/TOF was used to identify bacteria present in the fecal matter of NEC positive infants.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] This study focused on characterization of the fecal microbiota associated with NEC and did not address the mechanism of disease.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] There is hope that a similar technique could be used as a quick, diagnostic tool that would not require sequencing.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Another example of the diagnostic power of MALDI/TOF is in the area of cancer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Pancreatic cancer remains one of the most deadly and difficult to diagnose cancers.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Impaired cellular signaling due to mutations in membrane proteins has been long suspected to contribute to pancreatic cancer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] MALDI/TOF has been used to identify a membrane protein associated with pancreatic cancer and at one point may even serve as an early detection technique.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] MALDI/TOF can also potentially be used to dictate treatment as well as diagnosis.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] MALDI/TOF serves as a method for determining the drug resistance of bacteria, especially to β-lactams (Penicillin family).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The MALDI/TOF detects the presence of carbapenemases, which indicates drug resistance to standard antibiotics.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] It is predicted that this could serve as a method for identifying a bacterium as drug resistant in as little as three hours.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] This technique could help physicians decide whether to prescribe more aggressive antibiotics initially.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Following initial observations that some peptide-peptide complexes could survive MALDI deposition and ionization, studies of large protein complexes using MALDI-MS have been reported.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] While MALDI is a common technique for large macro-molecules, it is often possible to also analyze small molecules with mass below 1000 Da.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The problem with small molecules is that of matrix effects, where signal interference, detector saturation, or suppression of the analyte signal is possible since the matrices often consists of small molecules themselves.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] The choice of matrix is highly dependent on what molecules are to be analyzed.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] Due to MALDI being a soft ionization source, it is used on a wide variety of biomolecules.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] This has led to it being used in new ways such as MALDI-imaging mass spectrometry.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/matrix-assisted-laser-desorption-ionization] This technique allows for the imaging of the spatial distribution of biomolecules.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] The advantage of this method is that only the masses of the peptides have to be known.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] A disadvantage is that the protein sequence has to be present in the database of interest.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Additionally most PMF algorithms assume that the peptides come from a single protein.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] The presence of a mixture can significantly complicate the analysis and potentially compromise the results.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Typical for the PMF-based protein identification is the requirement for an isolated protein.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Mixtures exceeding a number of 2–3 proteins typically require the additional use of MS/MS-based protein identification to achieve sufficient specificity of identification.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Therefore, typical PMF samples are isolated proteins from two-dimensional gel electrophoresis (2D gels) or isolated SDS-PAGE bands.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Additional analyses by MS/MS can either be direct, e.g., MALDI-TOF/TOF analysis or downstream nanoLC-ESI-MS/MS analysis of gel spot eluates.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Due to the long, tedious process of analyzing proteins, peptide mass fingerprinting was developed.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Edman degradation was used in protein analysis, and it required almost an hour to analyze one amino acid residue.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] SDS-PAGE was also used to separate proteins in very complex mixtures, which also employed methods of electroblotting and staining.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Then, bands would be extracted from the gel and sequenced, automatically.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] A recurring problem in the process was that interfering proteins would also purify with the protein of interest.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] The sequences of these interfering proteins were compiled into what came to known as the Dayhoff database.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Ultimately, having the sequences of these known protein contaminants in databases decreased instrument time and expenses involved in protein analysis.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Protein samples can be derived from SDS-PAGE or reversed phase HPLC, and are then subject to some chemical modifications.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Disulfide bridges in proteins are reduced and cysteine amino acids are carbamidomethylated chemically or acrylamidated during the gel electrophoresis.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Then the proteins are cut into several fragments using proteolytic enzymes such as trypsin, chymotrypsin or Glu-C.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] A typical sample:protease ratio is 50:1.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] The proteolysis is typically carried out overnight and the resulting peptides are extracted with acetonitrile and dried under vacuum.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] The peptides are then dissolved in a small amount of distilled water or further concentrated and purified and are ready for mass spectrometric analysis.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] The digested protein can be analyzed with different types of mass spectrometers such as ESI-TOF or MALDI-TOF.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] MALDI-TOF is often the preferred instrument because it allows a high sample throughput and several proteins can be analyzed in a single experiment, if complemented by MS/MS analysis.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] LC/ESI-MS and CE/ESI-MS are also great techniques for peptide mass fingerprinting.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] A small fraction of the peptide (usually 1 microliter or less) is pipetted onto a MALDI target and a chemical called a matrix is added to the peptide mix.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Common matrices are sinapinic acid, Alpha-Cyano-4-hydroxycinnamic acid, and 2,3-Dihydroxybenzoic acid.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] The matrix molecules are required for the desorption of the peptide molecules.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Matrix and peptide molecules co-crystallize on the MALDI target and are ready to be analyzed.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] There is one predominantly MALDI-MS sample preparation technique, namely dried droplet technique.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] The target is inserted into the vacuum chamber of the mass spectrometer and the desorption and ionisation of the polypeptide fragments is initiated by a pulsed laser beam which transfers high amounts of energy into the matrix molecules.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] The energy transfer is sufficient to promote the ionisation and transition of matrix molecules and peptides from the solid phase into the gas phase.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] The ions are accelerated in the electric field of the mass spectrometer and fly towards an ion detector where their arrival is detected as an electric signal.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Their mass-to-charge ratio is proportional to their time of flight (TOF) in the drift tube and can be calculated accordingly.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Coupling ESI with capillary LC can separate peptides from protein digests, while obtaining their molecular masses at the same time.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Capillary electrophoresis coupled with ESI-MS is another technique; however, it works best when analyzing small amounts of proteins.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] The mass spectrometric analysis produces a list of molecular weights which is often called a peak list.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] The peptide masses are compared to protein databases such as Swissprot, which contain protein sequence information.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Software performs *in silico* digests on proteins in the database with the same enzyme (e.g. trypsin) used in the chemical cleavage reaction.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] The mass of these peptides is then calculated and compared to the peak list of measured masses.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] The results are statistically analyzed and possible matches are returned in a results table.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Proteins are vital macromolecules of all living organisms, with many functions such as the formation of structural fibers of muscle tissue, enzymatic digestion of food, or synthesis and replication of DNA.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] In addition, other kinds of proteins include antibodies that protect an organism from infection, and hormones that send important signals throughout the body.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Proteomics enables the identification of ever-increasing numbers of proteins.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] This varies with time and distinct requirements, or stresses, that a cell or organism undergoes.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The first studies of proteins that could be regarded as proteomics began in 1974, after the introduction of the two-dimensional gel and mapping of the proteins from the bacterium *Escherichia coli*.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] After genomics and transcriptomics, proteomics is the next step in the study of biological systems.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] It is more complicated than genomics because an organism's genome is more or less constant, whereas proteomes differ from cell to cell and from time to time.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Distinct genes are expressed in different cell types, which means that even the basic set of proteins produced in a cell must be identified.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] In the past this phenomenon was assessed by RNA analysis, which was found to lack correlation with protein content.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] It is now known that mRNA is not always translated into protein, and the amount of protein produced for a given amount of mRNA depends on the gene it is transcribed from and on the cell's physiological state.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Proteomics confirms the presence of the protein and provides a direct measure of its quantity.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Not only does the translation from mRNA cause differences, but many proteins also are subjected to a wide variety of chemical modifications after translation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The most common and widely studied post-translational modifications include phosphorylation and glycosylation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Many of these post-translational modifications are critical to the protein's function.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] One such modification is phosphorylation, which happens to many enzymes and structural proteins in the process of cell signaling.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Because protein phosphorylation is one of the most studied protein modifications, many "proteomic" efforts are geared to determining the set of phosphorylated proteins in a particular cell or tissue-type under particular circumstances.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] This alerts the scientist to the signaling pathways that may be active in that instance.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Ubiquitin is a small protein that may be affixed to certain protein substrates by enzymes called E3 ubiquitin ligases.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Determining which proteins are poly-ubiquitinated helps understand how protein pathways are regulated.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] This is, therefore, an additional legitimate "proteomic" study.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Similarly, once a researcher determines which substrates are ubiquitinated by each ligase, determining the set of ligases expressed in a particular cell type is helpful.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] In addition to phosphorylation and ubiquitination, proteins may be subjected to (among others) methylation, acetylation, glycosylation, oxidation, and nitrosylation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Some proteins undergo all these modifications, often in time-dependent combinations.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] This illustrates the potential complexity of studying protein structure and function.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] A cell may make different sets of proteins at different times or under different conditions, for example during development, cellular differentiation, cell cycle, or carcinogenesis.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Further increasing proteome complexity, as mentioned, most proteins are able to undergo a wide range of post-translational modifications.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Therefore, a "proteomics" study may become complex very quickly, even if the topic of study is restricted.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] In more ambitious settings, such as when a biomarker for a specific cancer subtype is sought, the proteomics scientist might elect to study multiple blood serum samples from multiple cancer patients to minimise confounding factors and account for experimental noise.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Thus, complicated experimental designs are sometimes necessary to account for the dynamic complexity of the proteome.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] In proteomics, there are multiple methods to study proteins.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Generally, proteins may be detected by using either antibodies (immunoassays), electrophoretic separation or mass spectrometry.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Antibodies to particular proteins, or their modified forms, have been used in biochemistry and cell biology studies.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] These are among the most common tools used by molecular biologists today.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] There are several specific techniques and protocols that use antibodies for protein detection.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay (ELISA) has been used for decades to detect and quantitatively measure proteins in samples.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The western blot may be used for detection and quantification of individual proteins, where in an initial step, a complex protein mixture is separated using SDS-PAGE and then the protein of interest is identified using an antibody.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Modified proteins may be studied by developing an antibody specific to that modification.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] For example, some antibodies only recognize certain proteins when they are tyrosine-phosphorylated, they are known as phospho-specific antibodies.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Also, there are antibodies specific to other modifications.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] These may be used to determine the set of proteins that have undergone the modification of interest.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Immunoassays can also be carried out using recombinantly generated immunoglobulin derivatives or synthetically designed protein scaffolds that are selected for high antigen specificity.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Such binders include single domain antibody fragments (Nanobodies), designed ankyrin repeat proteins (DARPins) and aptamers.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Disease detection at the molecular level is driving the emerging revolution of early diagnosis and treatment.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] A challenge facing the field is that protein biomarkers for early diagnosis may be present in very low abundance.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The lower limit of detection with conventional immunoassay technology is the upper femtomolar range (10−13 M).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Digital immunoassay technology has improved detection sensitivity three logs, to the attomolar range (10−16 M).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] This capability has the potential to open new advances in diagnostics and therapeutics, but such technologies have been relegated to manual procedures that are not well suited for efficient routine use.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] While protein detection with antibodies is still very common in molecular biology, other methods have been developed as well, that do not rely on an antibody.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] These methods offer various advantages, for instance they often are able to determine the sequence of a protein or peptide, they may have higher throughput than antibody-based, and they sometimes can identify and quantify proteins for which no antibody exists.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] One of the earliest methods for protein analysis has been Edman degradation (introduced in 1967) where a single peptide is subjected to multiple steps of chemical degradation to resolve its sequence.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] These early methods have mostly been supplanted by technologies that offer higher throughput.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] More recently implemented methods use mass spectrometry-based techniques, a development that was made possible by the discovery of "soft ionization" methods developed in the 1980s, such as matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization (MALDI) and electrospray ionization (ESI).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] These methods gave rise to the top-down and the bottom-up proteomics workflows where often additional separation is performed before analysis (see below).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] For the analysis of complex biological samples, a reduction of sample complexity is required.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] This may be performed off-line by one-dimensional or two-dimensional separation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] More recently, on-line methods have been developed where individual peptides (in bottom-up proteomics approaches) are separated using reversed-phase chromatography and then, directly ionized using ESI; the direct coupling of separation and analysis explains the term "on-line" analysis.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Several hybrid technologies use antibody-based purification of individual analytes and then perform mass spectrometric analysis for identification and quantification.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Examples of these methods are the MSIA (mass spectrometric immunoassay), developed by Randall Nelson in 1995, and the SISCAPA (Stable Isotope Standard Capture with Anti-Peptide Antibodies) method, introduced by Leigh Anderson in 2004.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Fluorescence two-dimensional differential gel electrophoresis (2-D DIGE) may be used to quantify variation in the 2-D DIGE process and establish statistically valid thresholds for assigning quantitative changes between samples.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Comparative proteomic analysis may reveal the role of proteins in complex biological systems, including reproduction.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] For example, treatment with the insecticide triazophos causes an increase in the content of brown planthopper (*Nilaparvata lugens* (Stål)) male accessory gland proteins (Acps) that may be transferred to females via mating, causing an increase in fecundity (i.e. birth rate) of females.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] To identify changes in the types of accessory gland proteins (Acps) and reproductive proteins that mated female planthoppers received from male planthoppers, researchers conducted a comparative proteomic analysis of mated *N. lugens* females.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The results indicated that these proteins participate in the reproductive process of *N. lugens* adult females and males.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Proteome analysis of *Arabidopsis* peroxisomes has been established as the major unbiased approach for identifying new peroxisomal proteins on a large scale.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] There are many approaches to characterizing the human proteome, which is estimated to contain between 20,000 and 25,000 non-redundant proteins.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The number of unique protein species likely will increase by between 50,000 and 500,000 due to RNA splicing and proteolysis events, and when post-translational modification also are considered, the total number of unique human proteins is estimated to range in the low millions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] In addition, the first promising attempts to decipher the proteome of animal tumors have recently been reported.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] This method was used as a functional method in *Macrobrachium rosenbergii* protein profiling.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Proteomics has steadily gained momentum over the past decade with the evolution of several approaches.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Few of these are new, and others build on traditional methods.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Mass spectrometry-based methods, affinity proteomics, and micro arrays are the most common technologies for large-scale study of proteins.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] There are two mass spectrometry-based methods currently used for protein profiling.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The more established and widespread method uses high resolution, two-dimensional electrophoresis to separate proteins from different samples in parallel, followed by selection and staining of differentially expressed proteins to be identified by mass spectrometry.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Despite the advances in 2-DE and its maturity, it has its limits as well.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The central concern is the inability to resolve all the proteins within a sample, given their dramatic range in expression level and differing properties.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The combination of pore size, and protein charge, size and shape can greatly determine migration rate which leads to other complications.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The second quantitative approach uses stable isotope tags to differentially label proteins from two different complex mixtures.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Here, the proteins within a complex mixture are labeled isotopically first, and then digested to yield labeled peptides.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The labeled mixtures are then combined, the peptides separated by multidimensional liquid chromatography and analyzed by tandem mass spectrometry.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Isotope coded affinity tag (ICAT) reagents are the widely used isotope tags.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] In this method, the cysteine residues of proteins get covalently attached to the ICAT reagent, thereby reducing the complexity of the mixtures omitting the non-cysteine residues.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Quantitative proteomics using stable isotopic tagging is an increasingly useful tool in modern development.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Firstly, chemical reactions have been used to introduce tags into specific sites or proteins for the purpose of probing specific protein functionalities.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The isolation of phosphorylated peptides has been achieved using isotopic labeling and selective chemistries to capture the fraction of protein among the complex mixture.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Secondly, the ICAT technology was used to differentiate between partially purified or purified macromolecular complexes such as large RNA polymerase II pre-initiation complex and the proteins complexed with yeast transcription factor.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Thirdly, ICAT labeling was recently combined with chromatin isolation to identify and quantify chromatin-associated proteins.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Finally ICAT reagents are useful for proteomic profiling of cellular organelles and specific cellular fractions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Another quantitative approach is the accurate mass and time (AMT) tag approach developed by Richard D.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Smith and coworkers at Pacific Northwest National Laboratory.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] In this approach, increased throughput and sensitivity is achieved by avoiding the need for tandem mass spectrometry, and making use of precisely determined separation time information and highly accurate mass determinations for peptide and protein identifications.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Affinity proteomics uses antibodies or other affinity reagents (such as oligonucleotide-based aptamers) as protein-specific detection probes.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Currently this method can interrogate several thousand proteins, typically from biofluids such as plasma, serum or cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] A key differentiator for this technology is the ability to analyze hundreds or thousands of samples in a reasonable timeframe (a matter of days or weeks); mass spectrometry-based methods are not scalable to this level of sample throughput for proteomics analyses.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Balancing the use of mass spectrometers in proteomics and in medicine is the use of protein micro arrays.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The aim behind protein micro arrays is to print thousands of protein detecting features for the interrogation of biological samples.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Antibody arrays are an example in which a host of different antibodies are arrayed to detect their respective antigens from a sample of human blood.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Another approach is the arraying of multiple protein types for the study of properties like protein-DNA, protein-protein and protein-ligand interactions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Ideally, the functional proteomic arrays would contain the entire complement of the proteins of a given organism.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The first version of such arrays consisted of 5000 purified proteins from yeast deposited onto glass microscopic slides.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Despite the success of the first chip, it was a greater challenge for protein arrays to be implemented.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Proteins are inherently much more difficult to work with than DNA.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] They have a broad dynamic range, are less stable than DNA and their structure is difficult to preserve on glass slides, though they are essential for most assays.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The global ICAT technology has striking advantages over protein chip technologies.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] This is a promising and newer microarray application for the diagnosis, study and treatment of complex diseases such as cancer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The technology merges laser capture microdissection (LCM) with micro array technology, to produce reverse-phase protein microarrays.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] In this type of microarrays, the whole collection of protein themselves are immobilized with the intent of capturing various stages of disease within an individual patient.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] When used with LCM, reverse phase arrays can monitor the fluctuating state of proteome among different cell population within a small area of human tissue.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] This is useful for profiling the status of cellular signaling molecules, among a cross-section of tissue that includes both normal and cancerous cells.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] This approach is useful in monitoring the status of key factors in normal prostate epithelium and invasive prostate cancer tissues.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] LCM then dissects these tissue and protein lysates were arrayed onto nitrocellulose slides, which were probed with specific antibodies.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] This method can track all kinds of molecular events and can compare diseased and healthy tissues within the same patient enabling the development of treatment strategies and diagnosis.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The ability to acquire proteomics snapshots of neighboring cell populations, using reverse-phase microarrays in conjunction with LCM has a number of applications beyond the study of tumors.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The approach can provide insights into normal physiology and pathology of all the tissues and is invaluable for characterizing developmental processes and anomalies.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Recent advancements in bioorthogonal chemistry have revealed applications in protein analysis.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The extension of using organic molecules to observe their reaction with proteins reveals extensive methods to tag them.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Unnatural amino acids and various functional groups represent new growing technologies in proteomics.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Specific biomolecules that are capable of being metabolized in cells or tissues are inserted into proteins or glycans.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The molecule will have an affinity tag, modifying the protein allowing it to be detected.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Azidohomoalanine (AHA) utilizes this affinity tag via incorporation with Met-t-RNA synthetase to incorporate into proteins.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] This has allowed AHA to assist in determine the identity of newly synthesized proteins created in response to perturbations and to identify proteins secreted by cells.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Recent studies using ketones and aldehydes condensations show that they are best suited for in vitro or cell surface labeling.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] However, using ketones and aldehydes as bioorthogonal reporters revealed slow kinetics indicating that while effective for labeling, the concentration must be high.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Certain proteins can be detected via their reactivity to azide groups.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Non-proteinogenic amino acids can bear azide groups which react with phosphines in Staudinger ligations.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] This reaction has already been used to label other biomolecules in living cells and animals.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The bioorthogonal field is expanding and is driving further applications within proteomics.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] It is worthwhile noting the limitations and benefits.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Rapid reactions can create bioconjuctions and create high concentrations with low amounts of reactants.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Contrarily slow kinetic reactions like aldehyde and ketone condensation while effective require a high concentration making it cost inefficient.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] One major outcome of research on human genes and proteins has been the identification of potential new drugs for the treatment of disease.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] This process relies on genome and proteome information to identify proteins associated with specific diseases, which can then be evaluated as therapeutic targets using computational approaches.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] For example, when a protein is implicated in a disease, knowledge of its three-dimensional structure can guide the design of drugs that interfere with its function.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] A molecule that fits into the active site of an enzyme but cannot be released can effectively inactivate the enzyme.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] This principle underlies many modern drug-discovery strategies, which aim to identify compounds capable of modulating or inhibiting disease-relevant proteins.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] As genetic differences among individuals are increasingly characterized, these approaches are expected to support the development of personalized medicines tailored to improve efficacy for individual patients.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] A branch of proteomics known as chemoproteomics provides a broad set of tools and techniques for identifying and characterizing the protein targets of drugs, thereby supporting drug discovery and development efforts.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] CETSA measures drug-induced changes in protein thermal stability in intact cells or tissues and, when combined with proteomics, enables the unbiased identification and ranking of on- and off-targets, as well as supporting phenotypic hit mechanism-of-action studies.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] PISA extends thermal-shift principles by integrating protein solubility changes across a temperature gradient, substantially increasing throughput and enabling multiplexed analysis of multiple compounds, concentrations, or time points.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] This approach facilitates high-content target deconvolution and comparative mechanism-of-action profiling, including applications in low-input or automated workflows.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Interaction proteomics is the analysis of protein interactions from scales of binary interactions to proteome- or network-wide.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Most proteins function via protein–protein interactions, and one goal of interaction proteomics is to identify binary protein interactions, protein complexes, and interactomes.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Several methods are available to probe protein–protein interactions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] While the most traditional method is yeast two-hybrid analysis, a powerful emerging method is affinity purification followed by protein mass spectrometry using tagged protein baits.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Other methods include surface plasmon resonance (SPR), protein microarrays, dual polarisation interferometry, microscale thermophoresis, kinetic exclusion assay, and experimental methods such as phage display and *in silico* computational methods.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Knowledge of protein-protein interactions is especially useful in regard to biological networks and systems biology, for example in cell signaling cascades and gene regulatory networks (GRNs, where knowledge of protein-DNA interactions is also informative).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Proteome-wide analysis of protein interactions, and integration of these interaction patterns into larger biological networks, is crucial towards understanding systems-level biology.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Expression proteomics includes the analysis of protein expression at a larger scale.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] It helps identify main proteins in a particular sample, and those proteins differentially expressed in related samples—such as diseased vs. healthy tissue.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] If a protein is found only in a diseased sample then it can be a useful drug target or diagnostic marker.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Proteins with the same or similar expression profiles may also be functionally related.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] There are technologies such as 2D-PAGE and mass spectrometry that are used in expression proteomics.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Understanding the proteome, the structure and function of each protein and the complexities of protein–protein interactions are critical for developing the most effective diagnostic techniques and disease treatments in the future.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] An interesting use of proteomics is using specific protein biomarkers to diagnose disease.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] A number of techniques allow to test for proteins produced during a particular disease, which helps to diagnose the disease quickly.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Techniques include western blot, immunohistochemical staining, enzyme linked immunosorbent assay (ELISA) or mass spectrometry.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Secretomics, a subfield of proteomics that studies secreted proteins and secretion pathways using proteomic approaches, has recently emerged as an important tool for the discovery of biomarkers of disease.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] In proteogenomics, proteomic technologies such as mass spectrometry are used for improving gene annotations.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Parallel analysis of the genome and the proteome facilitates discovery of post-translational modifications and proteolytic events, especially when comparing multiple species (comparative proteogenomics).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Structural proteomics includes the analysis of protein structures at large-scale.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] It compares protein structures and helps identify functions of newly discovered genes.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The structural analysis also helps to understand that where drugs bind to proteins and also shows where proteins interact with each other.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] This understanding is achieved using different technologies such as X-ray crystallography and NMR spectroscopy.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Much proteomics data is collected with the help of high throughput technologies such as mass spectrometry and microarray.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] It would often take weeks or months to analyze the data and perform comparisons by hand.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] For this reason, biologists and chemists are collaborating with computer scientists and mathematicians to create programs and data pipelines to computationally analyze the protein data.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Using bioinformatics techniques, researchers are capable of faster analysis and data storage.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] A good place to find lists of current programs and databases is on the ExPASy bioinformatics resource portal.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The applications of bioinformatics-based proteomics include medicine, disease diagnosis, biomarker identification, and many more.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Mass spectrometry and microarray produce peptide fragmentation information but do not give identification of specific proteins present in the original sample.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Due to the lack of specific protein identification, past researchers were forced to decipher the peptide fragments themselves.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] However, there are currently programs available for protein identification.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] These programs take the peptide sequences output from mass spectrometry and microarray and return information about matching or similar proteins.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] This is done through algorithms implemented by the program which perform alignments with proteins from known databases such as UniProt and PROSITE to predict what proteins are in the sample with a degree of certainty.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The biomolecular structure forms the 3D configuration of the protein.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Understanding the protein's structure aids in the identification of the protein's interactions and function.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] It used to be that the 3D structure of proteins could only be determined using X-ray crystallography and NMR spectroscopy.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] As of 2017, Cryo-electron microscopy is a leading technique, solving difficulties with crystallization (in X-ray crystallography) and conformational ambiguity (in NMR); resolution was 2.2Å as of 2015.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Now, through bioinformatics, there are computer programs that can in some cases predict and model the structure of proteins.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] These programs use the chemical properties of amino acids and structural properties of known proteins to predict the 3D model of sample proteins.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] This also allows scientists to model protein interactions on a larger scale.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] In addition, biomedical engineers are developing methods to factor in the flexibility of protein structures to make comparisons and predictions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Most programs available for protein analysis are not written for proteins that have undergone post-translational modifications.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Some programs will accept post-translational modifications to aid in protein identification but then ignore the modification during further protein analysis.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] It is important to account for these modifications since they can affect the protein's structure.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] In turn, computational analysis of post-translational modifications has gained the attention of the scientific community.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The current post-translational modification programs are only predictive.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Chemists, biologists and computer scientists are working together to create and introduce new pipelines that allow for analysis of post-translational modifications that have been experimentally identified for their effect on the protein's structure and function.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] One example of the use of bioinformatics and the use of computational methods is the study of protein biomarkers.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Computational predictive models have shown that extensive and diverse feto-maternal protein trafficking occurs during pregnancy and can be readily detected non-invasively in maternal whole blood.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] This computational approach circumvented a major limitation, the abundance of maternal proteins interfering with the detection of fetal proteins, to fetal proteomic analysis of maternal blood.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Computational models can use fetal gene transcripts previously identified in maternal whole blood to create a comprehensive proteomic network of the term neonate.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Such work shows that the fetal proteins detected in pregnant woman's blood originate from a diverse group of tissues and organs from the developing fetus.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The proteomic networks contain many biomarkers that are proxies for development and illustrate the potential clinical application of this technology as a way to monitor normal and abnormal fetal development.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] An information-theoretic framework has also been introduced for biomarker discovery, integrating biofluid and tissue information.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] This new approach takes advantage of functional synergy between certain biofluids and tissues with the potential for clinically significant findings not possible if tissues and biofluids were considered individually.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] By conceptualizing tissue-biofluid as information channels, significant biofluid proxies can be identified and then used for the guided development of clinical diagnostics.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Candidate biomarkers are then predicted based on information transfer criteria across the tissue-biofluid channels.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Significant biofluid-tissue relationships can be used to prioritize clinical validation of biomarkers.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] A number of emerging concepts have the potential to improve the current features of proteomics.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Obtaining absolute quantification of proteins and monitoring post-translational modifications are the two tasks that impact the understanding of protein function in healthy and diseased cells.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Further, the throughput and sensitivity of proteomic assays, often measured as samples analyzed per day and depth of proteome coverage, respectively, have driven development of cutting-edge instrumentation and methodologies.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] For many cellular events, the protein concentrations do not change; rather, their function is modulated by post-translational modifications (PTM).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Methods of monitoring PTM are an underdeveloped area in proteomics.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Selecting a particular subset of protein for analysis substantially reduces protein complexity, making it advantageous for diagnostic purposes where blood is the starting material.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Another important aspect of proteomics, yet not addressed, is that proteomics methods should focus on studying proteins in the context of the environment.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The increasing use of chemical cross-linkers, introduced into living cells to fix protein-protein, protein-DNA and other interactions, may ameliorate this problem partially.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The challenge is to identify suitable methods of preserving relevant interactions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Another goal for studying proteins is development of more sophisticated methods to image proteins and other molecules in living cells and real-time.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Advances in quantitative proteomics would clearly enable more in-depth analysis of cellular systems.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Transcriptional and translational responses to these perturbations results in functional changes to the proteome implicated in response to the stimulus.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Therefore, describing and quantifying proteome-wide changes in protein abundance is crucial towards understanding biological phenomenon more holistically, on the level of the entire system.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] In this way, proteomics can be seen as complementary to genomics, transcriptomics, epigenomics, metabolomics, and other -omics approaches in integrative analyses attempting to define biological phenotypes more comprehensively.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] As an example, *The Cancer Proteome Atlas* provides quantitative protein expression data for ~200 proteins in over 4,000 tumor samples with matched transcriptomic and genomic data from The Cancer Genome Atlas.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Similar datasets in other cell types, tissue types, and species, particularly using deep shotgun mass spectrometry, will be an immensely important resource for research in fields like cancer biology, developmental and stem cell biology, medicine, and evolutionary biology.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Characterizing the human plasma proteome has become a major goal in the proteomics arena, but it is also the most challenging proteomes of all human tissues.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] It contains immunoglobulin, cytokines, protein hormones, and secreted proteins indicative of infection on top of resident, hemostatic proteins.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] It also contains tissue leakage proteins due to the blood circulation through different tissues in the body.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The blood thus contains information on the physiological state of all tissues and, combined with its accessibility, makes the blood proteome invaluable for medical purposes.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] It is thought that characterizing the proteome of blood plasma is a daunting challenge.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The depth of the plasma proteome encompasses a dynamic range of more than 1010 between the highest abundant protein (albumin) and the lowest (some cytokines) and is thought to be one of the main challenges for proteomics.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Temporal and spatial dynamics further complicate the study of human plasma proteome.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] The turnover of some proteins is quite faster than others and the protein content of an artery may substantially vary from that of a vein.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] All these differences make even the simplest proteomic task of cataloging the proteome seem out of reach.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] To tackle this problem, priorities need to be established.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Capturing the most meaningful subset of proteins among the entire proteome to generate a diagnostic tool is one such priority.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Secondly, since cancer is associated with enhanced glycosylation of proteins, methods that focus on this part of proteins will also be useful.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Again: multiparameter analysis best reveals a pathological state.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] As these technologies improve, the disease profiles should be continually related to respective gene expression changes.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Due to the above-mentioned problems plasma proteomics remained challenging.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] However, technological advancements and continuous developments seem to result in a revival of plasma proteomics as it was shown recently by a technology called plasma proteome profiling.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Due to such technologies researchers were able to investigate inflammation processes in mice, the heritability of plasma proteomes as well as to show the effect of such a common life style change like weight loss on the plasma proteome.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Numerous journals are dedicated to the field of proteomics and related areas.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Note that journals dealing with *proteins* are usually more focused on structure and function while *proteomics* journals are more focused on the large-scale analysis of whole proteomes or at least large sets of proteins.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/proteomics] Some relevant proteomics journals are listed below (with their publishers).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The molecules of a given sample are ionized and the first spectrometer (designated **MS1**) separates these ions by their mass-to-charge ratio (often given as **m/z** or m/Q).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Ions of a particular m/z-ratio coming from MS1 are selected and then made to split into smaller fragment ions, e.g. by collision-induced dissociation, ion-molecule reaction, or photodissociation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] These fragments are then introduced into the second mass spectrometer (**MS2**), which in turn separates the fragments by their m/z-ratio and detects them.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The fragmentation step makes it possible to identify and separate ions that have very similar m/z-ratios in regular mass spectrometers.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Typical tandem mass spectrometry instrumentation setups include triple quadrupole mass spectrometer (QqQ), multi-sector mass spectrometer, ion trap, quadrupole–time of flight (Q-TOF), Fourier transform ion cyclotron resonance (FT-ICR), and hybrid mass spectrometers.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Triple quadrupole mass spectrometers use the first and third quadrupoles as mass filters.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] When analytes pass the second quadrupole, the fragmentation proceeds through collision with gas.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Q-TOF mass spectrometers combine quadrupole and TOF instruments, which together enable fragmentation experiments that yield highly accurate mass quantitations for product ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This is a method of mass spectrometry in which fragmented ion (*m*/*z*) ratios are determined through a time of flight measurement.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Hybrid mass spectrometers consist of more than two mass analyzers.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Multiple stages of mass analysis separation can be accomplished with individual mass spectrometer elements separated in space or using a single mass spectrometer with the MS steps separated in time.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] For tandem mass spectrometry in space, the different elements are often noted in a shorthand, giving the type of mass selector used.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] In tandem mass spectrometry *in space*, the separation elements are physically separated and distinct, although there is a physical connection between the elements to maintain high vacuum.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] These elements can be sectors, transmission quadrupole, or time-of-flight.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] When using multiple quadrupoles, they can act as both mass analyzers and collision chambers.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Common notation for mass analyzers is *Q* – quadrupole mass analyzer; *q* – radio frequency collision quadrupole; *TOF* – time-of-flight mass analyzer; *B* – magnetic sector, and *E* – electric sector.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The notation can be combined to indicate various hybrid instrument, for example *QqQ'* – triple quadrupole mass spectrometer; *QTOF* – quadrupole time-of-flight mass spectrometer (also *QqTOF*); and *BEBE* – four-sector (reverse geometry) mass spectrometer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] By doing tandem mass spectrometry *in time*, the separation is accomplished with ions trapped in the same place, with multiple separation steps taking place over time.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] A quadrupole ion trap or Fourier transform ion cyclotron resonance instrument can be used for such an analysis.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Trapping instruments can perform multiple steps of analysis, which is sometimes referred to as MS*n* (MS to the *n*).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Often the number of steps, *n*, is not indicated, but occasionally the value is specified; for example MS3 indicates three stages of separation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Tandem in time MS instruments do not use the modes described next, but typically collect all of the information from a precursor ion scan and a parent ion scan of the entire spectrum.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Each instrumental configuration utilizes a unique mode of mass identification.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] When tandem MS is performed with an in space design, the instrument must operate in one of a variety of modes.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] There are a number of different tandem MS/MS experimental setups and each mode has its own applications and provides different information.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Tandem MS in space uses the coupling of two instrument components which measure the same mass spectrum range but with a controlled fractionation between them in space, while tandem MS in time involves the use of an ion trap.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] There are four main scan experiments possible using MS/MS: precursor ion scan, product ion scan, neutral loss scan, and selected reaction monitoring.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] For a precursor ion scan, the product ion is selected in the second mass analyzer, and the precursor masses are scanned in the first mass analyzer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Note that precursor ion is synonymous with parent ion and product ion with daughter ion; however the use of these anthropomorphic terms is discouraged.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] In a product ion scan, a precursor ion is selected in the first stage, allowed to fragment and then all resultant masses are scanned in the second mass analyzer and detected in the detector that is positioned after the second mass analyzer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This experiment is commonly performed to identify transitions used for quantification by tandem MS.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] In a neutral loss scan, the first mass analyzer scans all the masses.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The second mass analyzer also scans, but at a set offset from the first mass analyzer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This offset corresponds to a neutral loss that is commonly observed for the class of compounds.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] In a constant-neutral-loss scan, all precursors that undergo the loss of a specified common neutral are monitored.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] To obtain this information, both mass analyzers are scanned simultaneously, but with a mass offset that correlates with the mass of the specified neutral.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Similar to the precursor-ion scan, this technique is also useful in the selective identification of closely related class of compounds in a mixture.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] In selected reaction monitoring, both mass analyzers are set to a selected mass.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This mode is analogous to selected ion monitoring for MS experiments.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] A selective analysis mode, which can increase sensitivity.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Fragmentation of gas-phase ions is essential to tandem mass spectrometry and occurs between different stages of mass analysis.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] There are many methods used to fragment the ions and these can result in different types of fragmentation and thus different information about the structure and composition of the molecule.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Often, the ionization process is sufficiently violent to leave the resulting ions with sufficient internal energy to fragment within the mass spectrometer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] If the product ions persist in their non-equilibrium state for a moderate amount of time before auto-dissociation this process is called metastable fragmentation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Nozzle-skimmer fragmentation refers to the purposeful induction of in-source fragmentation by increasing the nozzle-skimmer potential on usually electrospray based instruments.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Although in-source fragmentation allows for fragmentation analysis, it is not technically tandem mass spectrometry unless metastable ions are mass analyzed or selected before auto-dissociation and a second stage of analysis is performed on the resulting fragments.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] In-source fragmentation can be used in lieu of tandem mass spectrometry through the utilization of enhanced in-source fragmentation annotation (EISA) technology which generates fragmentation that directly matches tandem mass spectrometry data.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Fragments observed by EISA have higher signal intensity than traditional fragments which suffer losses in the collision cells of tandem mass spectrometers.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] EISA enables fragmentation data acquisition on MS1 mass analyzers such as time-of-flight and single quadrupole instruments.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] In-source fragmentation is often used in addition to tandem mass spectrometry (with post-source fragmentation) to allow for two steps of fragmentation in a pseudo MS3-type of experiment.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Post-source fragmentation is most often what is being used in a tandem mass spectrometry experiment.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Energy can also be added to the ions, which are usually already vibrationally excited, through post-source collisions with neutral atoms or molecules, the absorption of radiation, or the transfer or capture of an electron by a multiply charged ion.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Collision-induced dissociation (CID), also called collisionally activated dissociation (CAD), involves the collision of an ion with a neutral atom or molecule in the gas phase and subsequent dissociation of the ion.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] where the ion AB+ collides with the neutral species M and subsequently breaks apart.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The details of this process are described by collision theory.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Due to different instrumental configuration, two main different types of CID are possible: *(i)* beam-type (in which precursor ions are fragmented on-the-flight) and *(ii)* ion trap-type (in which precursor ions are first trapped, and then fragmented).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] A third and more recent type of CID fragmentation is higher-energy collisional dissociation (HCD).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] HCD is a CID technique specific to orbitrap mass spectrometers in which fragmentation takes place external to the ion trap, it happens in the HCD cell (in some instruments named "ion routing multipole").
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] HCD is a trap-type fragmentation that has been shown to have beam-type characteristics.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Freely available large scale high resolution tandem mass spectrometry databases exist (e.g.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] METLIN with 960,000 molecular standards each with experimental CID MS/MS data), and are typically used to facilitate small molecule identification.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The energy released when an electron is transferred to or captured by a multiply charged ion can induce fragmentation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] If an electron is added to a multiply charged positive ion, the Coulomb energy is liberated.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Adding an electron through an ion-ion reaction is called electron-transfer dissociation (ETD).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Similar to electron-capture dissociation, ETD induces fragmentation of cations (e.g. peptides or proteins) by transferring electrons to them.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Syka and Jarrod Marto at the University of Virginia.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] ETD cleaves randomly along the peptide backbone (c and z ions) while side chains and modifications such as phosphorylation are left intact.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The technique only works well for higher charge state ions (z>2), however relative to collision-induced dissociation (CID), ETD is advantageous for the fragmentation of longer peptides or even entire proteins.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This makes the technique important for top-down proteomics.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Much like ECD, ETD is effective for peptides with modifications such as phosphorylation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Electron-transfer and higher-energy collision dissociation (EThcD) is a combination ETD and HCD where the peptide precursor is initially subjected to an ion/ion reaction with fluoranthene anions in a linear ion trap, which generates c- and z-ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] In the second step HCD all-ion fragmentation is applied to all ETD derived ions to generate b- and y- ions prior to final analysis in the orbitrap analyzer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This method employs dual fragmentation to generate ion- and thus data-rich MS/MS spectra for peptide sequencing and PTM localization.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Following this transfer event, the electron-deficient anion undergoes internal rearrangement and fragments.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] NETD is the ion/ion analogue of electron-detachment dissociation (EDD).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] NETD is compatible with fragmenting peptide and proteins along the backbone at the Cα-C bond.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The resulting fragments are usually a•- and x-type product ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Electron-detachment dissociation (EDD) is a method for fragmenting anionic species in mass spectrometry.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] It serves as a negative counter mode to electron capture dissociation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Negatively charged ions are activated by irradiation with electrons of moderate kinetic energy.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The result is ejection of electrons from the parent ionic molecule, which causes dissociation via recombination.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Reaction between positively charged peptides and cationic reagents, also known as charge transfer dissociation (CTD), has recently been demonstrated as an alternative high-energy fragmentation pathway for low-charge state (1+ or 2+) peptides.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Initial reports are that CTD causes backbone Cα-C bond cleavage of peptides and provides a•- and x-type product ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] where $h\nu$ represents the photon absorbed by the ion.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Ultraviolet lasers can be used, but can lead to excessive fragmentation of biomolecules.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Infrared photons will heat the ions and cause dissociation if enough of them are absorbed.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This process is called infrared multiphoton dissociation (IRMPD) and is often accomplished with a carbon dioxide laser and an ion trapping mass spectrometer such as a FTMS.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Blackbody radiation can be used for photodissociation in a technique known as blackbody infrared radiative dissociation (BIRD).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] In the BIRD method, the entire mass spectrometer vacuum chamber is heated to create infrared light.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] BIRD uses this radiation to excite increasingly more energetic vibrations of the ions, until a bond breaks, creating fragments.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This is similar to infrared multiphoton dissociation which also uses infrared light, but from a different source.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] BIRD is most often used with Fourier transform ion cyclotron resonance mass spectrometry.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] With surface-induced dissociation (SID), the fragmentation is a result of the collision of an ion with a surface under high vacuum.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Today, SID is used to fragment a wide range of ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Years ago, it was only common to use SID on lower mass, singly charged species because ionization methods and mass analyzer technologies weren't advanced enough to properly form, transmit, or characterize ions of high m/z.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Over time, self-assembled monolayer surfaces (SAMs) composed of CF3(CF2)10CH2CH2S on gold have been the most prominently used collision surfaces for SID in a tandem spectrometer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] SAMs have acted as the most desirable collision targets due to their characteristically large effective masses for the collision of incoming ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Additionally, these surfaces are composed of rigid fluorocarbon chains, which don't significantly dampen the energy of the projectile ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The fluorocarbon chains are also beneficial because of their ability to resist facile electron transfer from the metal surface to the incoming ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] SID's ability to produce subcomplexes that remain stable and provide valuable information on connectivity is unmatched by any other dissociation technique.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Since the complexes produced from SID are stable and retain distribution of charge on the fragment, this produces a unique, spectra which the complex centers around a narrower m/z distribution.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The SID products and the energy at which they form are reflective of the strengths and topology of the complex.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The unique dissociation patterns help discover the Quaternary structure of the complex.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The symmetric charge distribution and dissociation dependence are unique to SID and make the spectra produced distinctive from any other dissociation technique.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The SID technique is also applicable to ion-mobility mass spectrometry (IM-MS).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Three different methods for this technique include analyzing the characterization of topology, intersubunit connectivity, and the degree of unfolding for protein structure.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Analysis of protein structure unfolding is the most commonly used application of the SID technique.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] For Ion-mobility mass spectrometry (IM-MS), SID is used for dissociation of the source activated precursors of three different types of protein complexes: C-reactive protein (CRP), transthyretin (TTR), and concanavalin A (Con A).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This method is used to observe the unfolding degree for each of these complexes.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] For this observation, SID showed the precursor ions' structures that exist before the collision with the surface.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] IM-MS utilizes the SID as a direct measure of the conformation for each proteins' subunit.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Fourier-transform ion cyclotron resonance are able to provide ultrahigh resolution and high mass accuracy to instruments that take mass measurements.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] These features make FT-ICR mass spectrometers a useful tool for a wide variety of applications such as several dissociation experiments such as collision-induced dissociation (CID, electron transfer dissociation (ETD), and others.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] In addition, surface-induced dissociation has been implemented with this instrument for the study of fundamental peptide fragmentation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Specifically, SID has been applied to the study of energetics and the kinetics of gas-phase fragmentation within an ICR instrument.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This approach has been used to understand the gas-phase fragmentation of protonated peptides, odd-electron peptide ions, non-covalent ligand-peptide complexes, and ligated metal clusters.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Quantitative proteomics is used to determine the relative or absolute amount of proteins in a sample.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Several quantitative proteomics methods are based on tandem mass spectrometry.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] MS/MS has become a benchmark procedure for the structural elucidation of complex biomolecules.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] One method commonly used for quantitative proteomics is isobaric tag labeling.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Isobaric tag labeling enables simultaneous identification and quantification of proteins from multiple samples in a single analysis.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] To quantify proteins, peptides are labeled with chemical tags that have the same structure and nominal mass, but vary in the distribution of heavy isotopes in their structure.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] These tags, commonly referred to as tandem mass tags, are designed so that the mass tag is cleaved at a specific linker region upon higher-energy collisional-induced dissociation (HCD) during tandem mass spectrometry yielding reporter ions of different masses.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Protein quantitation is accomplished by comparing the intensities of the reporter ions in the MS/MS spectra.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Two commercially available isobaric tags are iTRAQ and TMT reagents.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] An isobaric tag for relative and absolute quantitation (iTRAQ) is a reagent for tandem mass spectrometry that is used to determine the amount of proteins from different sources in a single experiment.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] It uses stable isotope labeled molecules that can form a covalent bond with the N-terminus and side chain amines of proteins.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The iTRAQ reagents are used to label peptides from different samples that are pooled and analyzed by liquid chromatography and tandem mass spectrometry.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The fragmentation of the attached tag generates a low molecular mass reporter ion that can be used to relatively quantify the peptides and the proteins from which they originated.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] A tandem mass tag (TMT) is an isobaric mass tag chemical label used for protein quantification and identification.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The tags contain four regions: mass reporter, cleavable linker, mass normalization, and protein reactive group.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] TMT reagents can be used to simultaneously analyze 2 to 11 different peptide samples prepared from cells, tissues or biological fluids.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Recent developments allow up to 16 and even 18 samples (16plex or 18plex respectively) to be analyzed.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The progress in data independent acquisition (DIA) enabled multiplexed quantitative proteomics with non-isobaric mass tags and a new method called plexDIA introduced in 2021.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This new approach increases the number of data points by parallelizing both samples and peptides, thus achieving multiplicative gains.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] It has the potential to continue scaling proteomic throughput with new mass tags and algorithms. plexDIA is applicable to both bulk and single-cell samples and is particularly powerful for single-cell proteomics.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Tandem mass spectrometry can be used for protein sequencing.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] When intact proteins are introduced to a mass analyzer, this is called "top-down proteomics" and when proteins are digested into smaller peptides and subsequently introduced into the mass spectrometer, this is called "bottom-up proteomics".
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Shotgun proteomics is a variant of bottom up proteomics in which proteins in a mixture are digested prior to separation and tandem mass spectrometry.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Tandem mass spectrometry can produce a peptide sequence tag that can be used to identify a peptide in a protein database.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] A notation has been developed for indicating peptide fragments that arise from a tandem mass spectrum.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Peptide fragment ions are indicated by a, b, or c if the charge is retained on the N-terminus and by x, y or z if the charge is maintained on the C-terminus.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The subscript indicates the number of amino acid residues in the fragment.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Superscripts are sometimes used to indicate neutral losses in addition to the backbone fragmentation, * for loss of ammonia and ° for loss of water.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Although peptide backbone cleavage is the most useful for sequencing and peptide identification other fragment ions may be observed under high energy dissociation conditions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] These include the side chain loss ions d, v, w and ammonium ions and additional sequence-specific fragment ions associated with particular amino acid residues.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Oligosaccharides may be sequenced using tandem mass spectrometry in a similar manner to peptide sequencing.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Fragmentation generally occurs on either side of the glycosidic bond (b, c, y and z ions) but also under more energetic conditions through the sugar ring structure in a cross-ring cleavage (x ions).
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Again trailing subscripts are used to indicate position of the cleavage along the chain.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] For cross ring cleavage ions the nature of the cross ring cleavage is indicated by preceding superscripts.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Tandem mass spectrometry has been applied to DNA and RNA sequencing.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] A notation for gas-phase fragmentation of oligonucleotide ions has been proposed.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Newborn screening is the process of testing newborn babies for treatable genetic, endocrinologic, metabolic and hematologic diseases.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The development of tandem mass spectrometry screening in the early 1990s led to a large expansion of potentially detectable congenital metabolic diseases that affect blood levels of organic acids.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] It has been shown that tandem mass spectrometry data is highly consistent across instrument and manufacturer platforms including quadrupole time-of-flight (QTOF) and Q Exactive instrumentation, especially at 20 eV.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Tandem mass spectrometry cannot be applied for single-cell analyses as it is insensitive to analyze such small amounts of a cell.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] These limitations are primarily due to a combination of inefficient ion production and ion losses within the instruments due to chemical noise sources of solvents.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Tandem mass spectrometry will be a useful tool for protein characterization, nucleoprotein complexes, and other biological structures.
[src:mass-spectrometry-proteomics/tandem-mass-spectrometry] However, some challenges left such as analyzing the characterization of the proteome quantitatively and qualitatively.
